The following result may seem trivial, but it describes a very fundamental property of the integers:

Note the uniqueness of qqqq and rrrr.

Section 4.1 (Edition 8, side 258-259) 2, 11, 15, 21, 43

Recall that aaaa divides bbbb (sometimes written as a\mid ba∣ba\mid ba∣b) if there exists another integer cccc such that b=c\cdot ab=c⋅ab=c\cdot ab=c⋅a.

  • Every third integer is divisible by 3333.
  • If aaaa or bbbb is divisible by cccc, then abababab is divisible by cccc.

The bruteforce approach: You can try to subtract 12121212 until you are left with a number between 0000 and 11111111.

Notice that we are really just computing modulo 12121212.

a) First, add the times 80+11=9180+11=9180+11=9180+11=91. So we want to find what 91919191 hours past midnight is on a 12121212-hour clock. This is the same as computing 91\mod1291mod  1291\mod1291mod12.

First, let's try the bruteforce approach starting with 91919191 and subtracting 12121212 until we have a number between 0000 and 11111111:

91\to 79\to 67\to 55\to 43\to 31\to 19\to \mathbf{7}91→79→67→55→43→31→19→791\to 79\to 67\to 55\to 43\to 31\to 19\to \mathbf{7}91→79→67→55→43→31→19→7

So the clock reads 7:007:007:007:00.

Here's another approach requiring less calculator abuse:

We can write 91 = 7\cdot 12+791=7⋅12+791 = 7\cdot 12+791=7⋅12+7 so we see that 91\mod 12=791mod  12=791\mod 12=791mod12=7 and we're done.

Remember that we can write a=q\cdot m + ra=q⋅m+ra=q\cdot m + ra=q⋅m+r for unique integers qqqq and rrrr. Then, a\mod m = ramod  m=ra\mod m = ramodm=r by definition.

Also, recall that a\equiv b\pmod ma≡b(modm)a\equiv b\pmod ma≡b(modm) means that m\mid (a-b)m∣(a−b)m\mid (a-b)m∣(a−b) (mmmm divides a-ba−ba-ba−b).

So, assume that a\mod m = b\mod mamod  m=bmod  ma\mod m = b\mod mamodm=bmodm and show that this implies that mmmm divides a-ba−ba-ba−b.

  1. Write a=q\cdot m+ra=q⋅m+ra=q\cdot m+ra=q⋅m+r and b=p\cdot m+sb=p⋅m+sb=p\cdot m+sb=p⋅m+s.
  2. By assumption a\mod m = b\mod mamod  m=bmod  ma\mod m = b\mod mamodm=bmodm, so we have r=sr=sr=sr=s.
  3. Write a-b = (q\cdot m+r) - (p\cdot m+s) = (q-p)m+(r-s)a−b=(q⋅m+r)−(p⋅m+s)=(q−p)m+(r−s)a-b = (q\cdot m+r) - (p\cdot m+s) = (q-p)m+(r-s)a−b=(q⋅m+r)−(p⋅m+s)=(q−p)m+(r−s).
  4. But r=sr=sr=sr=s so r-s=0r−s=0r-s=0r−s=0 and we have a-b= (q-p)ma−b=(q−p)ma-b= (q-p)ma−b=(q−p)m so m\mid(a-b)m∣(a−b)m\mid(a-b)m∣(a−b) and we are done.

There are many possible counterexamples.

b) Try m=5m=5m=5m=5 and a=ba=ba=ba=b.

However, 0\not\equiv 2\pmod 40≢2(mod4)0\not\equiv 2\pmod 40≡2(mod4) so we've found a counterexample.
